history.content:
The first student on the waitlist who can get into the class, does.

Student x cannot get into the class. Student y can.

Thus, assuming there is open space in the lecture, student y will get into the class.

children.subject:
As per @1901, there have been delays this semester in implementing that policy.

The answer to your second question is @1968.
Why don't I see this happening, then? It's been a while since phase 2 ended. I get that there are delays, but how long should I wait until I drop. I am in the position of student y.

If you are not declared, then there are no open seats for you (since the remaining seats in the class are all reserved).

Meanwhile, students who are EECS / declared CS majors can get into the class, and so they'll enroll in.
What if no one else enrolls? How long until non-cs will be able to enroll?

If the posted procedure is true, It did not seem to apply to my enrollment in a class.

I waitlisted for a class during the adjustment period and waitlisted for a discussion that had more available seats than people on the waitlist. Within a couple a days more people kept waitlisting that discussion and a day or two ago various were enrolled. There is now only one spot in that discussion and I am still on the waitlist. 

If I were say 9/15 (9th on the waitlist from 15 spots left), by this rule, shouldnt I have been enrolled despite whether I am declared or not? And how were other people, who waitlisted after I did, enroll in the discussion? Even if everyone infront of mef enrolled, there would have still been spots open.

history.content:
I am writing this question in reference to this posted on the EECS website:

Once Phase II is over (i.e. mid-August and mid-January for Fall and Spring semesters; also see the Schedule), during open enrollment, any UC student will be enrolled starting from the beginning of the existing waitlist. Neither major status nor class standing will impact enrollment at this point.

NOTE: Unless Cal Central does not ask for DIS sections to be chosen, students will need for there to be space in both the lecture and the secondary sections they choose to waitlist before being enrolled.

Say there are two non-cs/eecs students, x and y, who are trying to get into an upper division CS course. x is position 1 on the waitlist and y is position 2. Suppose that x is waitlisted in a full discussion, while y's discussion has many open seats. Would y have a better chance of getting into the course than student x? What exactly happens when the waitlist is processed? Is student x left on the waitlist while student y is enrolled?
